INSERT INTO questions (subject, topic, difficulty, question_text, choices, correct_answer, explanation, exam_type) VALUES
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','Who wrote the Philippine national anthem "Lupang Hinirang"?','[{"key":"A","text":"José Palma"},{"key":"B","text":"Julian Felipe"},{"key":"C","text":"Emilio Aguinaldo"},{"key":"D","text":"Andrés Bonifacio"}]','A','The lyrics of "Lupang Hinirang" were written by José Palma in 1899. Julian Felipe composed the music.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The first cry of Philippine revolution against Spain occurred in:','[{"key":"A","text":"Kawit, Cavite"},{"key":"B","text":"Balintawak or Pugad Lawin"},{"key":"C","text":"Malolos, Bulacan"},{"key":"D","text":"Intramuros, Manila"}]','B','The Cry of Pugad Lawin (also called Cry of Balintawak) on August 23, 1896, marked the start of the Philippine Revolution.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','Ferdinand Magellan arrived in the Philippines in:','[{"key":"A","text":"1521"},{"key":"B","text":"1565"},{"key":"C","text":"1571"},{"key":"D","text":"1599"}]','A','Magellan arrived in the Philippines on March 16, 1521, landing in Homonhon Island and later in Cebu, where he was killed in the Battle of Mactan.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','Who defeated Ferdinand Magellan in the Battle of Mactan?','[{"key":"A","text":"Rajah Humabon"},{"key":"B","text":"Sultan Kudarat"},{"key":"C","text":"Lapu-Lapu"},{"key":"D","text":"Andrés Bonifacio"}]','C','Lapu-Lapu, chieftain of Mactan, led the forces that killed Magellan on April 27, 1521. He is celebrated as the first Filipino hero.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The Katipunan was founded by:','[{"key":"A","text":"José Rizal"},{"key":"B","text":"Andrés Bonifacio"},{"key":"C","text":"Emilio Aguinaldo"},{"key":"D","text":"Apolinario Mabini"}]','B','The Kataastaasan Kagalanggalangang Katipunan (KKK) was founded by Andrés Bonifacio on July 7, 1892 in Manila.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','José Rizal was executed at what is now known as:','[{"key":"A","text":"Luneta Park (Rizal Park)"},{"key":"B","text":"Fort Santiago"},{"key":"C","text":"Intramuros"},{"key":"D","text":"Bagumbayan"}]','D','Rizal was executed at Bagumbayan (now Rizal Park/Luneta) on December 30, 1896. The park was later renamed in his honor.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The Philippine Declaration of Independence was proclaimed on June 12, 1898 in:','[{"key":"A","text":"Manila"},{"key":"B","text":"Malolos, Bulacan"},{"key":"C","text":"Kawit, Cavite"},{"key":"D","text":"Tarlac"}]','C','Emilio Aguinaldo proclaimed Philippine independence on June 12, 1898 in Kawit, Cavite, which is now celebrated as Independence Day.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','The Malolos Constitution of 1899 established the Philippines as a:','[{"key":"A","text":"Monarchy"},{"key":"B","text":"Military junta"},{"key":"C","text":"Federal republic"},{"key":"D","text":"Democratic republican government"}]','D','The Malolos Constitution established the First Philippine Republic under Emilio Aguinaldo as a democratic, republican government.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The Treaty of Paris (1898) transferred the Philippines from Spain to the United States for:','[{"key":"A","text":"₱20 million pesos"},{"key":"B","text":"$10 million"},{"key":"C","text":"$20 million"},{"key":"D","text":"Free of charge"}]','C','The Treaty of Paris signed on December 10, 1898 transferred the Philippines (and Guam and Puerto Rico) to the USA for $20 million.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','Who was the first Filipino President of the Commonwealth of the Philippines?','[{"key":"A","text":"Manuel L. Quezon"},{"key":"B","text":"Emilio Aguinaldo"},{"key":"C","text":"Sergio Osmeña"},{"key":"D","text":"Manuel Roxas"}]','A','Manuel L. Quezon was inaugurated as the first President of the Commonwealth of the Philippines on November 15, 1935.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','hard','The Propaganda Movement was primarily aimed at:','[{"key":"A","text":"Armed revolution against Spain"},{"key":"B","text":"Peaceful reforms and recognition of Filipino rights under Spanish rule"},{"key":"C","text":"Establishing trade with China"},{"key":"D","text":"Promoting the Catholic Church in the Philippines"}]','B','The Propaganda Movement (1880s-1890s) was a peaceful reform movement led by ilustrados like Rizal, del Pilar, and López Jaena, seeking equal rights and representation.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','Noli Me Tangere, José Rizal''s first novel, exposed the abuses of:','[{"key":"A","text":"American colonizers"},{"key":"B","text":"Spanish friars and colonial government"},{"key":"C","text":"Filipino ilustrados"},{"key":"D","text":"Chinese traders"}]','B','Noli Me Tangere (1887) depicted the abuses and corruption of Spanish colonialism and the Catholic clergy in the Philippines.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','The EDSA Revolution of 1986 ousted which Philippine president?','[{"key":"A","text":"Corazon Aquino"},{"key":"B","text":"Ferdinand Marcos"},{"key":"C","text":"Joseph Estrada"},{"key":"D","text":"Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo"}]','B','The People Power Revolution (EDSA 1986) was a non-violent uprising that ended Ferdinand Marcos''s 21-year rule and restored democracy.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The pre-colonial Filipino writing system is called:','[{"key":"A","text":"Alibata"},{"key":"B","text":"Baybayin"},{"key":"C","text":"Kudlit"},{"key":"D","text":"Abakada"}]','B','Baybayin is the pre-colonial writing system of the Philippines. "Alibata" is a misnomer coined by Paul Versoza; Baybayin is the accepted term.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','Miguel López de Legazpi established the first permanent Spanish settlement in the Philippines in:','[{"key":"A","text":"Cebu (1565)"},{"key":"B","text":"Manila (1571)"},{"key":"C","text":"Bohol (1563)"},{"key":"D","text":"Mindanao (1570)"}]','A','Legazpi established the first permanent Spanish settlement in Cebu in 1565. He later moved to Manila, making it the capital in 1571.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','hard','The Biak-na-Bato Pact (1897) resulted in:','[{"key":"A","text":"Philippine independence from Spain"},{"key":"B","text":"Aguinaldo''s exile to Hong Kong and temporary end of the revolution"},{"key":"C","text":"The arrest of Andres Bonifacio"},{"key":"D","text":"The start of the Philippine-American War"}]','B','The Pact of Biak-na-Bato (December 1897) provided for Aguinaldo''s voluntary exile to Hong Kong and monetary indemnity, temporarily halting the revolution.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The Gomburza martyrdom refers to the execution of three Filipino priests. Which of the following is one of them?','[{"key":"A","text":"Padre Damaso"},{"key":"B","text":"Padre José Burgos"},{"key":"C","text":"Padre Florentino"},{"key":"D","text":"Padre Salvi"}]','B','GOMBURZA stands for Mariano Gomez, José Burgos, and Jacinto Zamora — three Filipino secular priests executed on February 17, 1872.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','The period of Japanese occupation in the Philippines (1942-1945) is associated with:','[{"key":"A","text":"Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere"},{"key":"B","text":"Marshall Plan"},{"key":"C","text":"Truman Doctrine"},{"key":"D","text":"Commonwealth status"}]','A','Japan promoted the "Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere" ideology to justify its occupation and promote pan-Asian solidarity under Japanese leadership.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The Battle of Corregidor in 1942 resulted in:','[{"key":"A","text":"Filipino-American victory"},{"key":"B","text":"Japanese surrender in the Philippines"},{"key":"C","text":"Fall of Corregidor to Japanese forces"},{"key":"D","text":"Liberation of Manila"}]','C','The Fall of Corregidor on May 6, 1942 marked the complete Japanese takeover of the Philippines after Filipino-American forces surrendered.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','General Douglas MacArthur''s famous promise "I shall return" referred to his pledge to:','[{"key":"A","text":"Return to the United States"},{"key":"B","text":"Liberate the Philippines from Japanese occupation"},{"key":"C","text":"Re-invade Spain"},{"key":"D","text":"Return to his post in Australia"}]','B','MacArthur fled the Philippines on March 11, 1942, and vowed "I shall return" — a promise he fulfilled with the liberation of the Philippines in 1944-1945.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','hard','The Philippine-American War (1899-1902) was caused primarily by:','[{"key":"A","text":"Filipino rejection of the Treaty of Paris ceding the Philippines to the USA"},{"key":"B","text":"American refusal to pay Spain for the Philippines"},{"key":"C","text":"A Filipino attack on American ships"},{"key":"D","text":"Disagreements over the Malolos Constitution"}]','A','After Spain ceded the Philippines to the USA for $20 million, Filipinos who had expected independence fought the Americans. The war officially began on February 4, 1899.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The Philippines officially gained independence from the United States on:','[{"key":"A","text":"June 12, 1898"},{"key":"B","text":"July 4, 1946"},{"key":"C","text":"March 25, 1934"},{"key":"D","text":"November 15, 1935"}]','B','The Philippines gained full independence from the United States on July 4, 1946. Independence Day was later moved to June 12 to honor the 1898 proclamation.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','The Tydings-McDuffie Act (1934) provided for:','[{"key":"A","text":"Immediate Philippine independence"},{"key":"B","text":"A 10-year Commonwealth period leading to independence"},{"key":"C","text":"Permanent US territorial status for the Philippines"},{"key":"D","text":"Military alliance between the Philippines and the USA"}]','B','The Tydings-McDuffie Act (Philippine Independence Act) established a 10-year Commonwealth period (1935-1945) leading to full independence.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','Ninoy Aquino was assassinated on:','[{"key":"A","text":"February 25, 1986"},{"key":"B","text":"August 21, 1983"},{"key":"C","text":"September 21, 1972"},{"key":"D","text":"April 27, 1521"}]','B','Benigno "Ninoy" Aquino Jr. was assassinated at Manila International Airport (now NAIA) on August 21, 1983, after returning from exile.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','Martial Law in the Philippines under Marcos was declared on:','[{"key":"A","text":"September 21, 1972"},{"key":"B","text":"August 21, 1983"},{"key":"C","text":"February 25, 1986"},{"key":"D","text":"July 4, 1946"}]','A','Ferdinand Marcos declared Martial Law on September 21, 1972 through Proclamation No. 1081, beginning his authoritarian rule.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','hard','The Spoliarium, considered the greatest Philippine painting, was created by:','[{"key":"A","text":"Fernando Amorsolo"},{"key":"B","text":"Juan Luna"},{"key":"C","text":"Felix Resurreccion Hidalgo"},{"key":"D","text":"Carlos Francisco"}]','B','Juan Luna''s "Spoliarium" (1884) won the gold medal at the Exposición de Bellas Artes in Madrid, Spain. It is now displayed at the National Museum of Fine Arts.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The longest-running insurgency in Asia, still active in the Philippines, involves:','[{"key":"A","text":"New People''s Army (NPA)"},{"key":"B","text":"Abu Sayyaf"},{"key":"C","text":"Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF)"},{"key":"D","text":"Bangsamoro Islamic Freedom Fighters"}]','A','The Communist Party of the Philippines-New People''s Army (CPP-NPA) insurgency, which began in 1968, is considered the longest-running communist insurgency in Asia.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','Apolinario Mabini was known as:','[{"key":"A","text":"The Great Plebeian"},{"key":"B","text":"The Father of Philippine Democracy"},{"key":"C","text":"The Sublime Paralytic / The Brains of the Revolution"},{"key":"D","text":"The First Filipino Hero"}]','C','Apolinario Mabini was called "The Sublime Paralytic" and "The Brains of the Revolution" for his intellectual leadership and drafting of the Malolos Constitution.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The Philippine flag''s sun has how many rays?','[{"key":"A","text":"6"},{"key":"B","text":"7"},{"key":"C","text":"8"},{"key":"D","text":"12"}]','C','The Philippine flag features a sun with 8 rays, representing the 8 provinces that first revolted against Spain.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','The Galleon Trade between Manila and Acapulco operated from:','[{"key":"A","text":"1521-1898"},{"key":"B","text":"1565-1815"},{"key":"C","text":"1600-1800"},{"key":"D","text":"1600-1850"}]','B','The Manila-Acapulco Galleon Trade operated from 1565 to 1815, making Manila a major trading hub between Asia and the Americas.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','hard','The Visita General of 1739 and the General Inspection of 1741 were colonial measures that:','[{"key":"A","text":"Encouraged Filipino education"},{"key":"B","text":"Investigated abuses of the encomienda system"},{"key":"C","text":"Promoted friar land ownership"},{"key":"D","text":"Established the Audiencia in Manila"}]','B','These colonial inspections investigated the abuses of the encomienda system, which granted Spanish colonizers control over Filipino laborers.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The Battle of Mactan (1521) is significant because:','[{"key":"A","text":"Spain established its first colony in the Philippines"},{"key":"B","text":"The first Filipino hero repelled European colonizers"},{"key":"C","text":"It ended the Spanish-American War"},{"key":"D","text":"It began the Katipunan revolution"}]','B','The Battle of Mactan is significant as Lapu-Lapu''s forces killed Magellan and repelled the first European colonization attempt, making him the first Filipino hero.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','Which Philippine national hero was known as "Ama ng Katipunan" (Father of the Katipunan)?','[{"key":"A","text":"Emilio Aguinaldo"},{"key":"B","text":"Andres Bonifacio"},{"key":"C","text":"José Rizal"},{"key":"D","text":"Apolinario Mabini"}]','B','Andres Bonifacio is known as the "Father of the Katipunan" as he founded the revolutionary society. He is also called "The Great Plebeian."','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','hard','The Tejeros Convention of 1897 is historically significant because:','[{"key":"A","text":"It marked the founding of the Katipunan"},{"key":"B","text":"It resulted in Bonifacio''s ouster and the rise of Aguinaldo"},{"key":"C","text":"It proclaimed Philippine independence"},{"key":"D","text":"It ended the Philippine-American War"}]','B','At Tejeros (March 22, 1897), Aguinaldo was elected president over Bonifacio. This led to Bonifacio''s arrest and execution, a controversial event in Philippine history.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The Philippine national hero officially recognized through Republic Act 646 is:','[{"key":"A","text":"Andres Bonifacio"},{"key":"B","text":"Emilio Aguinaldo"},{"key":"C","text":"José Rizal"},{"key":"D","text":"Apolinario Mabini"}]','C','RA 646 (Rizal Law, 1956) designated José Rizal as the national hero and required the study of his works and writings.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','The Hukbalahap (Huk) movement after World War II was primarily a:','[{"key":"A","text":"Pro-American independence movement"},{"key":"B","text":"Communist-influenced peasant insurgency"},{"key":"C","text":"Japanese resistance group"},{"key":"D","text":"Religious uprising"}]','B','The Hukbalahap (People''s Army Against the Japanese) became a communist-led peasant insurgency in the postwar period, fighting for land reform and against poverty.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','Which Philippine president declared Martial Law in 1972?','[{"key":"A","text":"Corazon Aquino"},{"key":"B","text":"Ferdinand Marcos"},{"key":"C","text":"Ramon Magsaysay"},{"key":"D","text":"Diosdado Macapagal"}]','B','Ferdinand Marcos declared Martial Law on September 21, 1972 through Presidential Proclamation No. 1081.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','The 1987 Philippine Constitution was ratified under President:','[{"key":"A","text":"Ferdinand Marcos"},{"key":"B","text":"Fidel Ramos"},{"key":"C","text":"Corazon Aquino"},{"key":"D","text":"Joseph Estrada"}]','C','The 1987 Constitution (Freedom Constitution) was ratified on February 2, 1987, during the presidency of Corazon Aquino after the EDSA Revolution.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','hard','The Balangiga Massacre of 1901 during the Philippine-American War involved:','[{"key":"A","text":"The American massacre of Filipino civilians in Samar"},{"key":"B","text":"A surprise Filipino attack on American forces in Samar, followed by a brutal American retaliation"},{"key":"C","text":"The Japanese bombing of Balangiga town"},{"key":"D","text":"Spanish execution of Filipino revolutionaries"}]','B','In September 1901, Filipino guerrillas killed 48 US soldiers in Balangiga, Samar. In retaliation, US General Jacob Smith ordered the killing of all males over 10 — a major war atrocity.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','El Filibusterismo, Rizal''s second novel, was dedicated to:','[{"key":"A","text":"Apolinario Mabini"},{"key":"B","text":"GOMBURZA (Gomez, Burgos, Zamora)"},{"key":"C","text":"Andres Bonifacio"},{"key":"D","text":"Emilio Aguinaldo"}]','B','Rizal dedicated El Filibusterismo (1891) to the memory of Gomez, Burgos, and Zamora — the three martyred priests whose execution deeply influenced him.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','medium','The term "ilustrado" during the Spanish colonial period referred to:','[{"key":"A","text":"Spanish colonial officials"},{"key":"B","text":"Educated and wealthy Filipino elite"},{"key":"C","text":"Katipunero revolutionaries"},{"key":"D","text":"Spanish friars stationed in the Philippines"}]','B','Ilustrados were the Filipino educated class, often wealthy and educated in Europe, who led the Propaganda Movement. Examples: Rizal, del Pilar, López Jaena.','secondary'),
('General Education','Social Studies','easy','The three stars on the Philippine flag represent:','[{"key":"A","text":"The three major island groups: Luzon, Visayas, Mindanao"},{"key":"B","text":"Liberty, Equality, and Fraternity"},{"key":"C","text":"The executive, legislative, and judicial branches"},{"key":"D","text":"The three heroes: Rizal, Bonifacio, Aguinaldo"}]','A','The three stars on the Philippine flag represent the three major geographical divisions: Luzon, Visayas, and Mindanao.','secondary');
